This is a very large file! Let me focus on the specific issue which is about lambda parameter indentation. The key part of the issue is this:

The expected format is:
```kotlin
combine(
  Any(),
  Any()
) { a,
          b -> // This should be indented to column 14, but it's being indented to column 8
  TODO()
}
```

The problem occurs when the code style is NOT `ktlint_official`. When using `ktlint_official`, it works correctly.

Let me look at the function `calculateIndentOfFunctionLiteralParameters` around line 454-480, as this seems to be the key function that handles lambda parameter indentation:

```kotlin
private fun ASTNode.calculateIndentOfFunctionLiteralParameters() =
    if (codeStyle == ktlint_official || isFirstParameterOfFunctionLiteralPrecededByNewLine()) {
        // val fieldExample =
        //      LongNameClass {
        //              paramA,
        //              paramB,
        //              paramC ->
        //          ClassB(paramA, paramB, paramC)
        //      }
        indentConfig.indent.repeat(2)
    } else {
        // Allow default IntelliJ IDEA formatting:
        // val fieldExample =
        //     LongNameClass { paramA,
        //                     paramB,
        //                     paramC ->
        //         ClassB(paramA, paramB, paramC)
        //     }
        parent(CALL_EXPRESSION)
            ?.let { callExpression ->
                val textBeforeFirstParameter =
                    callExpression.findChildByType(REFERENCE_EXPRESSION)?.text +
                        " { "
                " ".repeat(textBeforeFirstParameter.length)
            }
            ?: indentConfig.indent.repeat(2)
    }

The indentation calculation seems to be relying on the text length of the function call and opening brace. This approach doesn't account for the specific formatting requirements when the code style differs from the official ktlint style. The method attempts to mimic IntelliJ IDEA's default formatting, but falls short in certain scenarios.

I'll examine the `visitLbrace` function to understand how it handles function literals and their indentation contexts. The function appears to be setting up nested indentation rules, first finding the matching right brace and establishing an outer indent context. Then it creates an additional inner context specifically for function literals, using the arrow symbol as a reference point.

The current challenge involves the `calculateIndentOfFunctionLiteralParameters` method, which seems to incorrectly calculate indentation by using the starting position of `combine { ` instead of accounting for existing parameter indentation. I'll investigate test cases to clarify the expected indentation behavior.

